name: Rumble
comments: 'Rumble' went through a name change between composing and record release. It was originally copyrighted as “Odd Ball” with composing credits to Link’s dad Fred Wray, Sr. and defacto manager Milt Grant, even though that classic guitar riff was undoubtedly Link’s creation. Link supposedly wasn’t interested in the business side of things and for many years that was handled by his brother Vernon, with their dad Fred Sr. being credited as composer on many of Link’s later recordings.

name: St. Louis Blues
comments: One of the most famous and widely recorded early blues songs. According to ASCAP it is "the most recorded song of the first half of the 20th Century". It is supposedly based on Handy’s experiences being penniless and sleeping on the streets of St. Louis in 1892.

Wine Me Up
comments: Carl Belew & Van Givens wrote this song. They wrote for 4-Star records at the time. They sold the rights to the song to Faron Young and Frank Oakley without permission from the label (they told Faron that their wives wrote the song). At the same time, Belew sold the rights to the song to a guy named Eddie Crandell.
